LA1311. Scattered weed in waste places near puebla. Collection Notes: The following notes apply to all LA1311 subunits. SAL395. 10/28/70. L. esculentum var. SLC. Santa Rosa Puebla. 12.1 miles South of San Francisco, at end of road, puebla of +/- 1000 people. On west side of road, behind dwellings, in waste places. Most abundant plant scrambling over ground, up walls, etc. #1-15 in a single population of +/- 50 plants, all in flower and ripe fruit. Fantastic array of types, hence individual notes and B/Wh photos. Suspect largely selfing, thus several may be repeats. Progeny tests should be interesting. Variation seen in leaf shape, hairiness (0, 1/2, + types), flower size, leaf color, fruit size, locule number (2-fasc.), shape,(spherical, oblate, slightly elongate). In separate groups to the west and higher ground collected several additional types that included plum and extra fasc. Types. Several plants said to be over 1 year old, another plant at least 3 x 4 meters dimension, extremely vigorous and productive. No pests, no pollinators seen. [Seed from 19 plants.] SAL395-1 moderately divided, hairs present, flowers [stigmas exserted] 0.5, 2 locules, cherry shape.

Home garden (1985).  One plant in dooryard garden with other vegetables and flowers. Typical SLC, with hairs, small flowers, stigmas barely exserted. Said to be spontaneous not sown. Fruit use desultory, said to be bitter. Photo of plant? General notes on SLC of San Juan del Oro region 10/29/1984: All = [?] SLC but with noted differences between collections. In most cases = single plants in dooryards, mostly not planted. None seen except in disturbed places, nearly always in gardens. Robust plants with highly divided leaves and good fruit set. Flowers generally tiny and scarcely or not exserted. Some claim flavor is good, others = bitter and used to cure chicken diseases. Km distances are all distances beyond San Juan del Oro.
